{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Request payload to the external classifier API includes the full taxonomy label list every time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: classifier request builder -> API client payload. A pure unit test of a helper can miss wiring errors where labels are dropped before dispatch. Rejected System because behavior text is about payload composition ('request ... includes ... labels'), not real network/OS effects. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because correctness does not depend on model judgment or multi-step agent decisions.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module with a stub transport/client that records outbound payloads. Invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert the captured request contains all expected labels (no omissions, no stale cache values) across repeated calls.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Out-of-taxonomy provider label is mapped to \"unknown\" before returning to caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug appears at response handoff: provider response parsing + taxonomy validator + public return path. Unit-only normalization tests can miss integration mistakes (e.g., parser bypasses validator). Rejected System because real HTTP is unnecessary; a stubbed provider response reproduces the failure. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because this checks deterministic guardrail logic, not model quality.","test_description":"Run module with a fake provider returning an invalid label (e.g., \"medical\"). Assert module returns exactly \"unknown\" and never forwards raw invalid label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.33,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Normalization is deterministic